.TH _PRINTF 1 "March 30, 2025" "Version 1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
_printf \- produce output according to a format

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include <stdarg.h>
.B #include <stdlib.h>
.B #include "main.h"

.B int _printf(const char *format, ...);

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B _printf
produces output according to a format as specified by the format string. The format string contains directives that are replaced by the values specified in subsequent arguments, which are passed using the `va_list` type.

The function will iterate over the format string, handle each directive, and print the corresponding values. Supported directives include:
.TP
.B %c
Prints a character, which is an integer argument interpreted as a character.
.TP
.B %s
Prints a string of characters (null-terminated).
.TP
.B %i or %d
Prints an integer in decimal format.
.TP
.B %%
Prints a literal '%' character.

.SH PARAMETERS
.TP
.B format
A format string containing zero or more directives.

.SH RETURN VALUE
The function returns the number of characters printed (excluding the null byte used to end output to strings). If an error occurs (e.g., if a directive is invalid), it returns \-1.

.SH FUNCTIONS
.TP
.B int handle_cases(const char *format, va_list args)
Handles the format specifiers for the \fB_printf\fP function. It processes the format string and prints the corresponding values from the `va_list`.

.TP
.B int _putchar(char c)
Prints a single character to the standard output.

.TP
.B int _print_int(int num)
Prints an integer in decimal format.

.TP
.B int _print_string(char *str)
Prints a string of characters (null-terminated).

.SH EXAMPLES
Here is an example usage of the \fB_printf\fP function:

.nf
#include "main.h"

int main(void)
{
    _printf("Hello, World!\n");
    _printf("Character: %c\n", 'H');
    _printf("String: %s\n", "Holberton");
    _printf("Integer: %d\n", 42);

    return (0);
}
.fi

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR printf (1), 
.BR va_list (3)

